panels.title: PII Remediation Suggestions and Best Practices
panels.text:
Sumo Logic has created a set of best practices for remediating any PII you discover in your account via this dashboard or other methods. Please refer to the following for a comprehensive guide: https://github.com/SumoLogic/sumologic-content/blob/master/Privacy-Insights%26GDPR/Privacy%20Insights%20Documentation.pdf

This dashboard attempts to surface possible PII data in logs, but by no means is it intended to be a comprehensive discovery of all possible PII data. Please use this dashboard as one element of a comprehensive strategy to discover all PII information you may be logging. 

At a high level generally the first step will be to click on any dashboard which appears to be a valid instance of PII noted and ensure the results are truly PII of some form.

Second, utilize masking/hashing or filtration of the data using our provided regexes to ensure future such items don't pass through to your logs in the future. Industry Best Practices dictate that systems should not log PII information unnecessarily. That said, Sumo Logic provides capabilities to filter, hash or mask portions of a log message that are sensitive so that information does not flow into the Sumo Logic service. These capabilities operate on the data at time of ingest and therefore cannot be applied retroactively to data already ingested. For information on how to do this, please refer to the following video: https://cl.ly/290x3C291C3h.

Another option regarding future ingested PII is to utilize partitioning with a lower retention period so that partitions/logs which may contain PII or fairly sensitive (or potentially "stale" data) are periodically wiped out. Options in terms of data partitioning are demonstrated within the following link: https://cl.ly/3g051E151m19.

Third, you should consider how to deal with the existing PII discovered within your account. 

Lastly, discussing internally how to prevent ingestion of sensitive data into your Sumo Logic account could also be a valid strategy to ensure no data leakage occurs. Some changes to your logging/data ingestion may be warranted depending on the results of these searches.

Note: It may be prudent to modify the searches in your results. If you note a high incidence rate of false positives you can modify searches to exclude specific source categories, hosts, or findings easily by clicking into each dashboard and modifying the displayed search terms to exclude results as desired. Please refer to https://help.sumologic.com/ for further info around tailoring your search results.
